1
00:00:10,469 --> 00:00:13,431
You refuse to hand Charlie over?

2
00:00:13,514 --> 00:00:16,350
What do you mean? Explain yourself, Phil.

3
00:00:17,601 --> 00:00:18,936
It's just how it sounds.

4
00:00:19,520 --> 00:00:22,815
Why should I have to
hand over my private property?

5
00:00:22,898 --> 00:00:25,151
It was something that had no owner.

6
00:00:25,234 --> 00:00:27,862
And I happened to pick it up.

7
00:00:29,321 --> 00:00:32,867
Deputy Graham. As I'm sure you're aware,

8
00:00:33,451 --> 00:00:36,036
we're investigating terrorism
and murder here.

9
00:00:36,537 --> 00:00:39,373
We need to question Charlie.

10
00:00:40,249 --> 00:00:42,376
Like I said, that's fine.

11
00:00:42,960 --> 00:00:46,255
On condition that it's recorded on video
and my designated lawyer is present.

12
00:00:46,756 --> 00:00:50,342
Assuming you aren't planning on
stealing Charlie, what's the problem?

13
00:00:53,179 --> 00:00:54,305
You leave me no choice.

14
00:00:55,055 --> 00:00:56,515
Phil, hand over your badge.

15
00:00:57,224 --> 00:00:59,560
You're suspended from duty indefinitely.

16
00:01:02,772 --> 00:01:03,814
On what grounds?

17
00:01:04,523 --> 00:01:05,816
Grounds?

18
00:01:05,900 --> 00:01:06,984
Well, let's see.

19
00:01:07,568 --> 00:01:12,156
You let Feyerabend get away,
you're hampering the investigation.

20
00:01:13,032 --> 00:01:14,074
Take your pick.

21
00:01:14,575 --> 00:01:18,871
As sheriff, I'm well within my rights
to stand you down.

22
00:01:20,831 --> 00:01:21,832
Look, Philip.

23
00:01:22,917 --> 00:01:26,212
I don't know what nonsense
that congresswoman's put in your head,

24
00:01:26,295 --> 00:01:28,547
but are you gonna toss away
your career and your pension?

25
00:01:28,631 --> 00:01:30,049
Think it over care...

26
00:01:31,425 --> 00:01:32,510
Hey, Phil.

27
00:01:42,478 --> 00:01:47,274
I see. I'll support you as far as I can.

28
00:01:47,858 --> 00:01:51,320
But I can't intervene
in sheriff's office HR matters.

29
00:01:51,403 --> 00:01:52,404
That'd be an issue.

30
00:01:53,113 --> 00:01:54,240
I get it.

31
00:01:54,323 --> 00:01:57,660
But never mind that.
Can you do something about the media?

32
00:01:57,743 --> 00:01:59,954
They've already sniffed out where I live.

33
00:02:00,454 --> 00:02:02,373
<i>I was the one who leaked your address.</i>

34
00:02:03,457 --> 00:02:04,458
What?

35
00:02:04,542 --> 00:02:06,585
They'd have found you sooner or later.

36
00:02:06,669 --> 00:02:11,090
And with them watching,
the FBI won't try to get heavy-handed.

37
00:02:11,173 --> 00:02:13,884
Just put up with it until
the transfer procedures are in order.

38
00:02:13,968 --> 00:02:16,887
<i>I'll be in touch.</i>

39
00:02:20,349 --> 00:02:21,475
Damned politicians.

40
00:02:32,570 --> 00:02:38,409
<i>This is truer than principles
Discovered by geniuses like XY</i>

41
00:02:38,492 --> 00:02:42,580
<i>You are so captivating
That I can't take my eyes off you</i>

42
00:02:42,663 --> 00:02:46,709
<i>We are merely beings who are just living</i>

43
00:02:46,792 --> 00:02:49,044
<i>But we are beings unlike any other</i>

44
00:02:49,128 --> 00:02:50,963
<i>You make me wonder</i>

45
00:02:51,046 --> 00:02:55,175
<i>Actors caught in a drama
Unaware of the ending</i>

46
00:02:55,259 --> 00:02:59,096
<i>Our "relationship chart" is still blank
And it bothers me</i>

47
00:02:59,179 --> 00:03:03,517
<i>We only want to share laughter
Yet somehow end up hurting each other</i>

48
00:03:03,601 --> 00:03:05,394
<i>It wasn't supposed to be like this</i>

49
00:03:05,477 --> 00:03:09,899
<i>I wonder what principles or clues
Apply to our relationship</i>

50
00:03:09,982 --> 00:03:14,778
<i>A stereo yearning to blend
Like left and right</i>

51
00:03:14,862 --> 00:03:16,864
<i>Could it be love?
I don't know</i>

52
00:03:16,947 --> 00:03:18,616
<i>Are we at odds?
I don't think so</i>

53
00:03:18,699 --> 00:03:22,536
<i>It's a frustrating thing
And I can't even tell if it's real</i>

54
00:03:22,620 --> 00:03:28,083
<i>Just how deep is our relationship?
Why can't it be measured?</i>

55
00:03:28,417 --> 00:03:30,252
<i>I want to know you
I want you to know me</i>

56
00:03:30,336 --> 00:03:34,423
<i>And what's the level of expectation
When we get to know each other?</i>

57
00:03:34,506 --> 00:03:40,971
<i>I know nothing else but the long-sought
Love, and I want to seek it out</i>

58
00:03:47,519 --> 00:03:49,188
<i>You make me wonder</i>

59
00:03:54,610 --> 00:03:55,611
<i>Just beyond words</i>

60
00:03:55,694 --> 00:03:58,197
<i>You make me wonder</i>

61
00:03:59,573 --> 00:04:04,119
EPISODE 12
SEXUAL DIMORPHISM

62
00:04:04,203 --> 00:04:06,330
It's the deputy sheriff. Roll the camera.

63
00:04:15,506 --> 00:04:16,924
Can't get a good shot.

64
00:04:17,841 --> 00:04:19,551
Should we just come back tomorrow?

65
00:04:20,886 --> 00:04:21,929
I'm back.

66
00:04:22,972 --> 00:04:26,225
I bought what you asked for.
Check if anything's missing. Grace?

67
00:04:26,308 --> 00:04:27,851
Thanks.

68
00:04:27,935 --> 00:04:31,605
That's a big help.
Those people never let up.

69
00:04:32,189 --> 00:04:34,858
Oh, looks like they're leaving.
They sure have it tough.

70
00:04:34,942 --> 00:04:36,944
How's Charlie? Nothing new?

71
00:04:37,027 --> 00:04:39,613
Nope. He's been home all day.

72
00:04:40,197 --> 00:04:43,826
Did you know, Phil? He's really smart.

73
00:04:43,909 --> 00:04:48,330
I gave him a book of crossword puzzles
and he solved them all in no time.

74
00:04:48,414 --> 00:04:49,623
Really?

75
00:04:50,165 --> 00:04:52,543
I'm glad you're both getting along.

76
00:04:53,585 --> 00:04:55,254
<i>Hi, Charlie. How've you been?</i>

77
00:04:55,838 --> 00:04:58,048
<i>What are you calling on? Your phone?</i>

78
00:04:58,757 --> 00:05:02,845
It's a tablet. Phil gave it to me
after you left last night.

79
00:05:02,928 --> 00:05:06,890
<i>Nice. So how's the new place?
Things going well?</i>

80
00:05:06,974 --> 00:05:08,058
'Cause we're almost out.

81
00:05:08,142 --> 00:05:10,602
Geez. We've got enough of it.

82
00:05:11,270 --> 00:05:13,439
<i>Grace is always fussing over me.</i>

83
00:05:13,522 --> 00:05:16,567
That probably means it's going well then.

84
00:05:18,277 --> 00:05:19,278
Charlie.

85
00:05:20,154 --> 00:05:22,614
What about you though?

86
00:05:23,282 --> 00:05:24,283
<i>Me?</i>

87
00:05:24,867 --> 00:05:28,370
I mean… you're all good?

88
00:05:28,454 --> 00:05:33,751
<i>Yeah. I've got my regular checkup
at the Kornberg Institute this weekend.</i>

89
00:05:35,627 --> 00:05:38,338
I think I'm pretty healthy though.

90
00:05:39,048 --> 00:05:40,674
My body's lighter somehow.

91
00:05:41,592 --> 00:05:43,927
And I feel extra strong.

92
00:05:45,054 --> 00:05:47,264
<i>Oh, yeah?</i>

93
00:05:47,347 --> 00:05:48,348
Yeah.

94
00:05:48,974 --> 00:05:51,185
My senses are really sharp too.

95
00:05:54,772 --> 00:05:56,023
I think

96
00:05:56,565 --> 00:05:59,318
someone other than Phil and Grace
used to use this room.

97
00:06:01,278 --> 00:06:02,279
Suspended?

98
00:06:02,863 --> 00:06:06,200
Yeah. I'm sorry. I...

99
00:06:06,283 --> 00:06:08,243
Oh, well, what can you do.

100
00:06:08,327 --> 00:06:11,163
And it's a dangerous job,
so maybe it's for the best.

101
00:06:11,246 --> 00:06:12,748
We've got Charlie to worry about too.

102
00:06:12,831 --> 00:06:14,374
Hey…

103
00:06:14,458 --> 00:06:18,629
I know, the two of us could open
a massage parlor here. What do you think?

104
00:06:21,173 --> 00:06:24,259
At this hour? Is it the press again?

105
00:06:24,343 --> 00:06:25,427
Wait, let me...

106
00:06:26,303 --> 00:06:27,763
Yes, who is it?

107
00:06:28,430 --> 00:06:30,182
Oh, Ronnie.

108
00:06:30,265 --> 00:06:32,476
Evening, Grace.

109
00:06:32,559 --> 00:06:34,353
What a surprise.

110
00:06:34,436 --> 00:06:37,147
We hardly ever see you here.

111
00:06:37,231 --> 00:06:38,774
Come on in.

112
00:06:38,857 --> 00:06:42,194
That's okay. I was in the neighborhood.
Just thought I'd drop by.

113
00:06:42,778 --> 00:06:44,404
Mind if I borrow Phil for a bit?

114
00:06:44,488 --> 00:06:47,491
Sure thing.
I won't even charge you interest!

115
00:06:50,202 --> 00:06:52,830
Grace hasn't changed a bit.

116
00:06:54,498 --> 00:06:57,793
Yeah, she's basically led
a sheltered life. Never had it rough.

117
00:06:58,377 --> 00:07:02,506
Don't you wanna make sure
it stays that way?

118
00:07:03,507 --> 00:07:06,260
You understand, don't you, Phil?

119
00:07:06,343 --> 00:07:08,637
That monkey's like a spark to dry tinder.

120
00:07:09,596 --> 00:07:10,597
That may be.

121
00:07:11,306 --> 00:07:14,643
But it's the folks 'round here
who're feeding the fire.

122
00:07:16,478 --> 00:07:20,399
You put the Humanzee in there?
In your dead daughter's room?

123
00:07:21,567 --> 00:07:23,360
That's ancient history.

124
00:07:25,237 --> 00:07:26,321
If you say so.

125
00:07:27,447 --> 00:07:29,783
Better head home. Here.

126
00:07:31,618 --> 00:07:32,744
Ronnie.

127
00:07:32,828 --> 00:07:34,496
Take it.

128
00:07:34,580 --> 00:07:38,208
You deserve it
with all the good work you do.

129
00:07:43,255 --> 00:07:46,925
That coward ain't sheriff material.

130
00:07:47,009 --> 00:07:49,344
You should stand for election next time.

131
00:07:49,928 --> 00:07:51,972
I'll drum up the votes for ya.

132
00:07:52,556 --> 00:07:53,807
Good one, Ronnie.

133
00:07:56,351 --> 00:07:58,061
Call me if you need anything.

134
00:07:59,688 --> 00:08:03,942
I couldn't keep a lid on the violence.
I'm responsible too.

135
00:08:10,908 --> 00:08:12,284
Hi, Charlie.

136
00:08:12,868 --> 00:08:15,037
How do you like your new home?

137
00:08:15,454 --> 00:08:17,372
It's comfortable.

138
00:08:17,456 --> 00:08:20,500
Sorry for lying to you last time.

139
00:08:20,584 --> 00:08:22,294
This is my wife, Grace.

140
00:08:22,377 --> 00:08:26,632
Nice to meet you. It's my first time
coming to a research lab.

141
00:08:26,715 --> 00:08:29,593
We're happy you're here. Please, this way.

142
00:08:31,470 --> 00:08:34,973
Okay, Charlie. We just need to measure
your physical strength, then we're done.

143
00:08:37,392 --> 00:08:38,894
Everything looks normal.

144
00:08:39,394 --> 00:08:41,521
I wasn't sure how'd he be,

145
00:08:41,605 --> 00:08:43,690
but I think we can relax for now.

146
00:08:48,070 --> 00:08:49,404
Weird.

147
00:08:49,488 --> 00:08:52,449
This was custom-made to Humanzee specs.

148
00:08:52,532 --> 00:08:54,826
What on earth's going on?

149
00:08:55,452 --> 00:08:58,163
Dr. Fowler. It's…

150
00:09:09,800 --> 00:09:11,426
Something's abnormal with Charlie?

151
00:09:12,094 --> 00:09:15,389
Yes. Compare this
with the data from last time.

152
00:09:18,475 --> 00:09:20,686
You can see that his bones have
suddenly become thicker,

153
00:09:20,769 --> 00:09:24,064
and his muscle mass has
increased significantly.

154
00:09:24,147 --> 00:09:28,277
His blood testosterone
and androgen levels have also spiked.

155
00:09:28,360 --> 00:09:31,947
If he were human, he'd probably be
at Stage II or III on the Tanner scale...

156
00:09:32,030 --> 00:09:33,907
Whoa there, Doc.

157
00:09:33,991 --> 00:09:37,286
We're not college professors, remember?

158
00:09:37,369 --> 00:09:39,329
Explain it in language we can understand.

159
00:09:40,998 --> 00:09:42,332
Apologies.

160
00:09:42,416 --> 00:09:46,003
To put it plainly, right now, Charlie is…

161
00:09:48,672 --> 00:09:50,966
Hitting puberty.

162
00:09:56,388 --> 00:09:57,848
I got to the ceiling.

163
00:09:58,515 --> 00:09:59,975
Should we redo it?

164
00:10:03,478 --> 00:10:07,316
Puberty? As in puberty puberty?

165
00:10:08,358 --> 00:10:12,404
Yes. He's developing what we call
secondary sex characteristics.

166
00:10:12,904 --> 00:10:16,700
Humans and chimps go through
the same sexual maturation process

167
00:10:16,783 --> 00:10:17,909
to reach adulthood.

168
00:10:18,452 --> 00:10:20,746
However, for some reason

169
00:10:20,829 --> 00:10:23,081
Charlie never showed any signs of it

170
00:10:23,165 --> 00:10:25,208
when he reached the normal age
for either species.

171
00:10:25,917 --> 00:10:29,796
Frankly speaking,
I'm not sure why it's happening now.

172
00:10:29,880 --> 00:10:32,883
Perhaps Dr. Grossman arranged
things this way.

173
00:10:33,467 --> 00:10:36,887
Or maybe the recent drastic changes
in Charlie's environment

174
00:10:36,970 --> 00:10:40,140
have flipped some genetic switch.

175
00:10:40,724 --> 00:10:43,935
Losing his adoptive parents,
in particular,

176
00:10:44,019 --> 00:10:46,605
must have caused him
a great deal of stress.

177
00:10:47,230 --> 00:10:49,900
But there's nothing wrong
with him, is there?

178
00:10:50,609 --> 00:10:53,570
It just means he's growing up.

179
00:10:53,653 --> 00:10:55,864
Instead of worrying,
we should celebrate with a cake.

180
00:10:57,866 --> 00:10:59,409
S'pose so.

181
00:10:59,493 --> 00:11:01,912
Can't say I remember
my own folks sitting me down

182
00:11:01,995 --> 00:11:04,331
to talk about
secondary sex characteristics.

183
00:11:04,414 --> 00:11:06,083
S'cause you're a guy.

184
00:11:06,166 --> 00:11:07,626
Well, so's Charlie.

185
00:11:08,543 --> 00:11:12,130
Anyway, Doc, "abnormal" sounds like
a little bit of an overstatement.

186
00:11:12,214 --> 00:11:14,841
Shouldn't we just leave him be
and let nature take its course?

187
00:11:16,051 --> 00:11:19,554
No one knows what course it will take.

188
00:11:19,638 --> 00:11:23,225
Charlie's the only Humanzee
on the planet, after all.

189
00:11:23,308 --> 00:11:26,853
His species is a complete unknown.

190
00:11:28,939 --> 00:11:30,148
That's a new record.

191
00:11:30,232 --> 00:11:34,027
A perfect 1023 moves with no mistakes
in under five minutes. Incredible.

192
00:11:34,111 --> 00:11:35,946
You owe me ten bucks.

193
00:11:37,906 --> 00:11:38,907
Sorry.

194
00:11:40,492 --> 00:11:41,993
I'm hungry.

195
00:11:44,955 --> 00:11:46,832
Do you like it, Lucy?

196
00:11:46,915 --> 00:11:48,458
Yeah. It's delicious.

197
00:11:48,542 --> 00:11:50,710
I think I'm getting the hang
of the flavors.

198
00:11:51,294 --> 00:11:55,340
Phil, you could try eating the vegan food
I make for Charlie too.

199
00:11:55,424 --> 00:11:58,385
It's good for you,
and it might get rid of that beer belly.

200
00:11:58,468 --> 00:12:00,387
Gimme a break.

201
00:12:00,470 --> 00:12:04,516
I'll take my weekend beer and steak
over my health, thanks.

202
00:12:04,599 --> 00:12:07,352
Even if I end up senile
in an old folks' home.

203
00:12:07,436 --> 00:12:09,104
What if you end up with no teeth?

204
00:12:11,481 --> 00:12:13,567
I've never lost a tooth.

205
00:12:13,650 --> 00:12:15,777
So you still have your baby teeth?

206
00:12:17,737 --> 00:12:20,615
Phil, are you in contact
with Representative Linares?

207
00:12:21,533 --> 00:12:26,288
Yeah, though I can hardly ever
get a hold of her from this end.

208
00:12:26,371 --> 00:12:30,792
It's always her getting in touch with me.
"Sign this, sign that."

209
00:12:30,876 --> 00:12:33,295
What about the court case
for Charlie's citizenship?

210
00:12:33,378 --> 00:12:35,380
Right, heard about that.

211
00:12:36,006 --> 00:12:38,675
Well, check this out.
It's a book she wrote ages ago.

212
00:12:38,758 --> 00:12:42,429
Her take on animal rights
in here is pretty radical.

213
00:12:42,512 --> 00:12:45,849
Her opinions are
way more extreme than I realized.

214
00:12:46,349 --> 00:12:49,436
Pretty fascinating, but I'm surprised
she managed to get elected.

215
00:12:50,020 --> 00:12:52,856
Lucy, how many Americans do you think

216
00:12:52,939 --> 00:12:55,984
read what the candidates have written
before they vote?

217
00:12:56,067 --> 00:12:57,110
It's true.

218
00:12:57,194 --> 00:13:00,322
Charlie definitely needs
some kind of rights.

219
00:13:00,405 --> 00:13:03,742
Way things are now,
he couldn't even get a driver's license.

220
00:13:04,910 --> 00:13:09,080
But animal rights?
That's a ridiculous idea.

221
00:13:09,664 --> 00:13:13,793
Sure, I'm against senseless cruelty
to animals, same as the next guy.

222
00:13:13,877 --> 00:13:17,297
But it's only natural
for humans to put themselves first.

223
00:13:17,881 --> 00:13:19,424
Then what about Charlie?

224
00:13:20,008 --> 00:13:22,344
Charlie, well, he's half-human, ain't he?

225
00:13:22,427 --> 00:13:25,889
They can just make
a special Humanzee category for him.

226
00:13:27,307 --> 00:13:28,892
You think so?

227
00:13:28,975 --> 00:13:31,269
Yeah. After all,

228
00:13:31,353 --> 00:13:33,980
he's got nothing to do
with the rest of the animals.

229
00:13:34,064 --> 00:13:37,651
Rights are something humans thought up
for human society.

230
00:13:37,734 --> 00:13:40,153
Charlie, put that book down
till after dinner.

231
00:13:43,281 --> 00:13:47,160
Well, I guess maybe
that is the default attitude.

232
00:13:47,744 --> 00:13:52,165
I mean, I'm avoiding animal products
as much as I can now,

233
00:13:52,249 --> 00:13:55,877
but I'm not like Gare, I don't feel guilty
about my past behavior,

234
00:13:55,961 --> 00:13:59,923
and I don't feel like eating steak is
the same as cannibalism.

235
00:14:00,006 --> 00:14:04,427
It does gross me out when I see
celebs wearing fur though.

236
00:14:06,137 --> 00:14:09,140
I know. Totally inconsistent, right?

237
00:14:09,933 --> 00:14:14,020
Maybe it's speciesist of me to say this,

238
00:14:14,104 --> 00:14:18,316
but can we really ever
get rid of all that stuff?

239
00:14:18,400 --> 00:14:20,777
Like, could we give animals legal rights?

240
00:14:23,071 --> 00:14:25,156
It's no good. I can't get it all straight.

241
00:14:25,240 --> 00:14:28,743
This problem's way too big
for one high schooler.

242
00:14:28,827 --> 00:14:32,163
Like Phil said, it's got nothing
directly to do with your problem, Charlie.

243
00:14:32,747 --> 00:14:33,915
My problem?

244
00:14:33,999 --> 00:14:38,128
Dr. Grossman.
You're going to look for him, right?

245
00:14:38,837 --> 00:14:39,838
Yeah.

246
00:14:40,338 --> 00:14:43,258
If he's still alive,
I need to find him as soon as possible.

247
00:14:44,050 --> 00:14:46,094
Why's that?

248
00:14:46,845 --> 00:14:48,763
Well, Feyerabend's searching for him too.

249
00:14:49,264 --> 00:14:51,349
That's what he said, at least.

250
00:14:51,933 --> 00:14:54,227
What if Grossman joins up with the ALA?

251
00:14:55,562 --> 00:14:59,566
Yeah, that would be
a truly bad combination.

252
00:14:59,649 --> 00:15:03,987
He's not just a danger to human society.
He's a danger to us too.

253
00:15:04,529 --> 00:15:08,283
We don't know why
Dr. Grossman created a Humanzee.

254
00:15:09,743 --> 00:15:11,244
That's why you want to find him?

255
00:15:11,328 --> 00:15:14,247
Yeah. That's why I want to meet him.

256
00:15:14,748 --> 00:15:16,124
I want to know who I am.

257
00:15:16,833 --> 00:15:18,960
And why was I born.

258
00:15:21,921 --> 00:15:26,301
I told you before
that it's just me and my mom, right?

259
00:15:26,843 --> 00:15:27,843
Yeah.

260
00:15:28,428 --> 00:15:32,349
Well, I was conceived
through artificial insemination.

261
00:15:32,932 --> 00:15:34,684
- You were?
- Yep.

262
00:15:35,185 --> 00:15:37,687
Neither my mom nor I have ever met him.

263
00:15:38,313 --> 00:15:42,150
The sperm bank keeps
its donors' personal info private.

264
00:15:42,901 --> 00:15:45,153
All I have is his IQ and academic record,

265
00:15:45,236 --> 00:15:47,822
and the age he was
when he donated the sperm.

266
00:15:47,906 --> 00:15:50,450
Plus this one blurry photo.

267
00:15:51,076 --> 00:15:53,078
I've never told anyone all this before.

268
00:15:53,703 --> 00:15:55,663
It just seemed like
it would be a pain in the ass.

269
00:15:55,705 --> 00:15:59,209
Though to be honest,
I don't feel like it's that big a deal.

270
00:15:59,834 --> 00:16:02,921
My mom was super matter-of-fact about it
even when I was little.

271
00:16:03,004 --> 00:16:05,382
It wasn't about infertility or anything.

272
00:16:05,465 --> 00:16:07,592
She just said,
"You don't need a man to have a kid."

273
00:16:08,343 --> 00:16:11,221
Weirdly, it's kinda like your situation.

274
00:16:11,304 --> 00:16:13,848
Born through
unnatural reproductive technology,

275
00:16:13,932 --> 00:16:15,975
never met my dad,

276
00:16:16,059 --> 00:16:19,771
though you're obviously a much rarer case.

277
00:16:19,854 --> 00:16:24,275
Apparently tons of kids in the States are
conceived using sperm banks now.

278
00:16:24,984 --> 00:16:28,863
It's just, Feyerabend made it
pretty clear that he knew.

279
00:16:28,947 --> 00:16:31,282
- When you were in that cabin?
- Yeah.

280
00:16:32,242 --> 00:16:36,663
He actually broke into my house, so I'm
sure he's done all kinds of snooping.

281
00:16:37,330 --> 00:16:39,791
But it really shook me
when he brought it up.

282
00:16:39,874 --> 00:16:42,919
And since then,
something about it's been nagging at me.

283
00:16:43,962 --> 00:16:47,590
Is that why you wanted to be friends?

284
00:16:48,299 --> 00:16:51,511
Because we were both born through
unnatural reproductive technology?

285
00:16:52,011 --> 00:16:56,474
Nah, not at all.
I just thought you were interesting.

286
00:16:57,058 --> 00:16:58,893
And I never get bored talking to you.

287
00:16:59,894 --> 00:17:02,397
Does that mean you like me?

288
00:17:04,232 --> 00:17:06,109
Maybe, I guess?

289
00:17:06,860 --> 00:17:08,862
Then do you want to mate with me?

290
00:17:12,907 --> 00:17:14,868
Oh, right, humans don't say "mate."

291
00:17:15,452 --> 00:17:17,120
Fuck? Have sex?

292
00:17:18,204 --> 00:17:21,082
Why… with me?

293
00:17:22,041 --> 00:17:23,042
Because I want to.

294
00:17:26,629 --> 00:17:27,630
Sure.

295
00:17:28,840 --> 00:17:31,509
Does that mean you consent to mate?

296
00:17:32,385 --> 00:17:34,220
Consent? Well…

297
00:17:35,430 --> 00:17:37,056
It means I don't hate the idea.

298
00:17:38,975 --> 00:17:39,976
But…

299
00:17:41,352 --> 00:17:43,605
Wait, hang on. Do you mean now?

300
00:17:43,688 --> 00:17:45,190
Or whenever.

301
00:17:46,775 --> 00:17:49,152
I'm flattered,
but I think I'd rather not right this sec.

302
00:17:49,778 --> 00:17:52,113
Why not?
Even though you don't hate the idea?

303
00:17:52,947 --> 00:17:55,909
I mean, I guess

304
00:17:55,992 --> 00:17:59,579
I don't wanna do it
unless it's something I really want.

305
00:17:59,662 --> 00:18:01,831
And that's not how I feel right now.

306
00:18:02,540 --> 00:18:05,335
Would it be different if I were human?

307
00:18:05,418 --> 00:18:08,171
What? If you were human?

308
00:18:09,756 --> 00:18:12,050
'Sup, Lucy. Hop in.

309
00:18:15,011 --> 00:18:16,763
I don't really know.

310
00:18:17,806 --> 00:18:19,390
I mean, what about you?

311
00:18:19,808 --> 00:18:22,227
Do you think you can let go of the fact

312
00:18:22,310 --> 00:18:25,230
that you're a Humanzee, Charlie?

313
00:18:30,693 --> 00:18:34,739
It's Mom! I better get back. I'll get Phil
to take me since it's past dark.

314
00:18:37,575 --> 00:18:40,453
Sorry I couldn't give you what you wanted.

315
00:18:41,246 --> 00:18:42,831
That's okay. See you.

316
00:18:49,337 --> 00:18:51,381
For now, how about this.

317
00:18:57,345 --> 00:18:58,346
See ya.

318
00:19:00,515 --> 00:19:05,019
Oh yeah, by the way,
maybe call it "making love" instead.

319
00:19:05,103 --> 00:19:06,896
It's kinda old-fashioned,
but it's romantic.

320
00:19:14,404 --> 00:19:16,489
<i>I meant to kiss him on the cheek,</i>

321
00:19:17,407 --> 00:19:19,951
<i>but maybe that was his mouth?</i>

322
00:19:24,455 --> 00:19:26,875
JEFFERSON CITY, MISSOURI

323
00:19:26,958 --> 00:19:29,335
This way. The doctor's given permission.

324
00:19:31,713 --> 00:19:33,923
Though I doubt there's much point.

325
00:19:34,007 --> 00:19:36,718
He won't even speak to his lawyers.

326
00:19:36,801 --> 00:19:40,346
Thank you, Mr. Prosecutor.
We'll take it from here.

327
00:19:41,931 --> 00:19:43,016
You've got 15 minutes.

328
00:19:51,149 --> 00:19:54,402
Major Lesley K. Lippman.

329
00:19:54,485 --> 00:19:57,030
Joined the ALA after you were discharged.

330
00:20:01,034 --> 00:20:04,078
Hoping for some juicy plea deal, huh?

331
00:20:04,621 --> 00:20:07,373
Okay, here's a deal for you.

332
00:20:07,457 --> 00:20:10,335
Tell us everything you know about the ALA,

333
00:20:10,418 --> 00:20:14,172
and we'll let you choose between hanging
and the electric chair. How's that sound?

334
00:20:15,256 --> 00:20:18,676
Major. Your war is over.

335
00:20:18,760 --> 00:20:22,847
You lost. The ALA are powerless now.

336
00:20:22,931 --> 00:20:26,392
You shat all over your shiny war record.
But then you know that.

337
00:20:27,977 --> 00:20:30,355
Got nothin' to say?

338
00:20:33,983 --> 00:20:35,818
Catch Charlie.

339
00:20:37,153 --> 00:20:39,614
That's the FBI's goal, isn't it?

340
00:20:39,697 --> 00:20:42,909
To get him on a tight leash.

341
00:20:42,992 --> 00:20:45,036
You… Let go!

342
00:20:46,412 --> 00:20:49,791
Hey, what're you doing? Get away from him.
That's it, you're done here.

343
00:20:49,874 --> 00:20:52,377
Wait, our time's not up yet.

344
00:20:52,460 --> 00:20:56,172
Too bad. His lawyers are here too.
Now get out.

345
00:21:02,512 --> 00:21:04,973
NORTH DAKOTA

346
00:21:05,598 --> 00:21:07,016
Secretary Alcott.

347
00:21:07,100 --> 00:21:09,060
Tell us about the alleged
illegal donations.

348
00:21:09,143 --> 00:21:11,729
Is it true you worked to kill
the proposed animal welfare bill

349
00:21:11,813 --> 00:21:15,108
for the benefit
of the food processing industry?

350
00:21:15,191 --> 00:21:16,401
Secretary Alcott.

351
00:21:16,484 --> 00:21:19,821
There are reports you're under
investigation by a citizen's group.

352
00:21:20,405 --> 00:21:22,031
That's absurd.

353
00:21:22,115 --> 00:21:26,244
As I've just explained to its supporters.

354
00:21:26,327 --> 00:21:27,954
But it's a huge issue!

355
00:21:28,037 --> 00:21:30,707
- Mr. Secretary.
- Secretary Alcott.

356
00:21:30,790 --> 00:21:32,417
- Please answer the question!
- Sir!

357
00:21:32,500 --> 00:21:33,501
Sir, please.

358
00:21:35,336 --> 00:21:39,674
What? You got that? We need to avoid
an indictment at all costs.

359
00:21:39,757 --> 00:21:43,469
I'm headed back to Washington now.
Tell the president...

360
00:21:44,429 --> 00:21:47,473
Hey, what gives?
This isn't the way to the airport.

361
00:21:48,266 --> 00:21:49,892
Hey. Did you hear me?

362
00:22:04,657 --> 00:22:07,201
That mask… You're…

363
00:22:20,840 --> 00:22:25,553
<i>You might be the one I'm searching for</i>

364
00:22:25,636 --> 00:22:31,267
<i>Make this moment last for evermore</i>

365
00:22:31,350 --> 00:22:34,896
<i>Starting my day just the same as always</i>

366
00:22:34,979 --> 00:22:38,983
<i>Even when night ends
And then the dawn finds its way</i>

367
00:22:39,067 --> 00:22:42,487
<i>Hey, that's why I rush back into the flow</i>

368
00:22:42,570 --> 00:22:46,407
<i>Facing all these
Super crazy hectic days I know</i>

369
00:22:46,491 --> 00:22:50,453
<i>Singing while it's stabbing my brain</i>

370
00:22:50,536 --> 00:22:54,207
<i>Just like filling up the holes remained</i>

371
00:22:54,290 --> 00:22:57,794
<i>I'll keep on breaking through
Without stopping</i>

372
00:22:57,877 --> 00:22:59,629
<i>Even if insane</i>

373
00:22:59,712 --> 00:23:01,130
<i>Are you sure?</i>

374
00:23:01,214 --> 00:23:04,884
<i>I know it's boring, right?
I pray softly</i>

375
00:23:04,967 --> 00:23:08,971
<i>Even if I live how I want, I'm lonely</i>

376
00:23:09,055 --> 00:23:12,517
<i>Stacking fragile things
That will fade someday</i>

377
00:23:12,600 --> 00:23:16,938
<i>Just same as you
I am also just lonely, fall away</i>

378
00:23:17,021 --> 00:23:18,272
<i>Turn It Up!</i>

379
00:23:18,356 --> 00:23:20,900
<i>There's no way I can stop now</i>

380
00:23:20,983 --> 00:23:22,026
<i>Turn It Up!</i>

381
00:23:22,110 --> 00:23:24,695
<i>Let it sway with a gentle sound</i>

382
00:23:24,779 --> 00:23:25,947
<i>Turn It Up!</i>

383
00:23:26,030 --> 00:23:28,366
<i>Every thought I have of you</i>

384
00:23:28,449 --> 00:23:29,617
<i>Turn It Up!</i>

385
00:23:29,700 --> 00:23:32,537
<i>Riding straight to happiness too</i>

386
00:23:47,844 --> 00:23:49,846
Subtitle: Annie Chen

